1. cs.DB (Database): The paper focuses on similarity joins, which is a common operation in data cleaning and falls under the domain of databases. 
2. cs.IR (Information Retrieval): Similarity joins are also relevant to information retrieval, as finding similar strings can be useful in tasks such as document clustering and search. 
3. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper proposes a new partition-based method for similarity joins, which involves designing efficient data structures and algorithms. 
4. cs.CL (Computation and Language): The paper deals with string similarity, which is a common problem in natural language processing (NLP) tasks such as spelling correction and entity resolution. 
5. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): Similarity joins are also relevant to machine learning and AI, as they can be used for tasks such as record linkage and entity resolution in large datasets.
